  "prompt": "Startup Law: How common is the anti-dilution provision for VCs in a Series A round?",
  "response": "Anti-dilution provisions are very common in Series A venture capital investments. Here's a breakdown:\n\n1. Prevalence:\n- Nearly universal in Series A and later funding rounds\n- Almost always included in VC term sheets\n- Protects investors from equity value reduction\n\n2. Types of Anti-Dilution Provisions:\n- Full Ratchet: Most investor-friendly\n- Weighted Average: More balanced approach\n- Broad-based Weighted Average: Most startup-friendly version\n\n3. Typical Characteristics:\n- Triggered by subsequent financing rounds at lower valuations\n- Adjusts investor's ownership percentage\n- Helps maintain investor's economic interests\n\n4. Rationale:\n- Compensates investors for potential value erosion\n- Provides downside protection\n- Incentivizes investors to participate in risky early-stage investments\n\n5. Negotiation Dynamics:\n- Standard practice in venture investing\n- Founders typically cannot avoid these provisions entirely\n- Terms can be negotiated to balance investor and founder interests\n\nWhile specific details vary, anti-dilution provisions are considered standard in almost all Series A venture capital investments.",
